        <h2 id="vs-related">Digital marketing vs traditional marketing</h2>
        <p>Both work. The difference is what you can measure and how quickly you can react.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Digital marketing</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Every impression tracked to a specific ad or page</li>
              <li>Targeting down to postcode, keyword, or behaviour</li>
              <li>Budget adjustments in minutes, not months</li>
              <li>Content compounds — an article ranks for years</li>
              <li>Small budgets can compete with large brands</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Traditional marketing</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Broad reach in a single placement (TV, print, OOH)</li>
              <li>Higher trust in some categories (finance, healthcare)</li>
              <li>Harder to attribute revenue to individual placements</li>
              <li>Budgets set months in advance, hard to reallocate</li>
              <li>Better for mass-market awareness campaigns</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 digital marketing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with the customer journey.</strong> Map every touchpoint from awareness to purchase before picking channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Own your audience.</strong> Email lists and SEO traffic are yours; platform followers are rented from the algorithm.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish weekly, not sporadically.</strong> Compounding channels reward consistency more than genius.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure the funnel, not the channel.</strong> A channel that produces cheap clicks but no revenue is not working.</li>
          <li><strong>Reallocate every 30 days.</strong> Move budget from lagging channels to the top three performers.</li>
          <li><strong>Split brand and performance.</strong> Track them separately or brand will always lose to short-term performance metrics.</li>
          <li><strong>Automate before you scale.</strong> Marketing automation cuts human errors and frees time for creative work.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake &mdash; chasing every channel</div>
          <p>New teams often spread thin across 6-7 channels and win at none. Pick two channels aligned with your customer's habits, execute them relentlessly for 90 days, then add a third only after the first two are dialled in.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common digital marketing mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Vanity metrics obsession</strong> &mdash; celebrating impressions and follower counts instead of revenue.</li>
          <li><strong>No attribution model</strong> &mdash; running six channels without knowing which is producing the leads.</li>
          <li><strong>Paid-only strategy</strong> &mdash; stopping ads means stopping traffic; no compounding asset built.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring email</strong> &mdash; the highest-ROI channel is often the least prioritised.</li>
          <li><strong>Set-and-forget</strong> &mdash; algorithms and audience preferences shift; monthly reviews are non-negotiable.</li>
        </ul>

